  "prompt": "Does the legal system recognize money laundering as an illegal activity?",
  "response": "Yes, the legal system in most countries, including China, recognizes money laundering as an illegal activity. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (dirty money) appear legal or \"clean.\" It typically involves three stages: placement, layering, and integration.\n\nIn China, the Anti-Money Laundering Law was enacted to combat money laundering activities. The law establishes a framework for preventing and detecting money laundering, and it requires financial institutions and certain non-financial institutions to implement measures to identify and report suspicious transactions. The Chinese government has also established the China Anti-Money Laundering Monitoring and Analysis Center (CAMLMAC) to oversee and coordinate anti-money laundering efforts.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe and may include fines, imprisonment, and confiscation of assets. The legal system in China, as in many other countries, is committed to combating money laundering to maintain the integrity of the financial system and to prevent criminal activities.",
